[start section id="20112"]

#1 Resected stage II colon cancer with multiple recurrences
She has now had resection of her most recent recurrence in January of this year.  She has recovered nicely.  Because she had multiple recurrences, special studies were obtained that demonstrated microsatellite instability.  This was later determined to be a BRAF epigenetic mutation rather than a somatic mutation.  Her CT is without evidence of metastatic disease, and her CEA is back to normal.  I will see her in three-months for repeat clinical assessment with cross-sectional imaging and laboratory studies.  There is no role for chemotherapy here, escpecially given the MSI-H nature of her T2 tumor.  She should be re-scoped in about a year's time.
#2 Breast nodule
This feels completely benign in nature.  However, there is no way to be 100% certain.  I discussed this with her.  Will continue to follow this clinically.  I do not believe we need any advanced imaging or biopsies at this time.  She concurs with that.  She has agreed to call me if this increases in size or becomes tender in any way.
#3 Diarrhea
This is under good control on her current regimen.  I have refilled her prescription for the cholestyramine.
#4 Insomnia
It has been a number of years since she has seen her primary-care physician.  I refilled her Ativan prescription, which she uses as a sleep aid and has been doing so nightly for at least the last 5-10 years.
#5 Hypertension
I have also refilled her prescription for the diltiazem.
Follow-up:  I would like to have her follow-up with her primary-care physician.  It has been a number of years since she has been seen at the Frankfort State Medical Center out in Walnut Creek.  I have asked her to schedule an appointment with Dr. Taylor out there, who has seen her in the past.  I discussed with her that it is probably more appropriate for him to follow things like insomnia and hypertension while I continue to follow her cancer-related complaints.  He is also much closer to her home and much more convenient for her to see.  I will see her back in three-months' time with a repeat mammogram, as it has been two years, and the studies as noted above.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at JDO.

