[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Hollingsworth's oncological history is as follows:
1.  2003--Mrs. Hollingsworth underwent a resection of a T2, N0 adenocarcinoma of the right colon.
2.  April 2006--Mrs. Hollingsworth underwent a left nephrectomy for what turned out to be oncocytoma, as well as a wide local resection with end-to-end reanastomosis of an ileal colonic T2, grade 4, adenocarcinoma.  Again this was N0, M0.
3.  November 2008--the patient's CEA is 6.1 at this time, which is slightly above her baseline in the mid 4s.  Repeat CT scanning suggests a new mass in the pelvis.
4.  December 2008--excision of the mass in the abdomen reveals no evidence of malignancy.
5.  January 2010--has a T2, N0, M0 colon cancer resected by Dr. Sullins.  Recovers nicely.
Mrs. Hollingsworth returns today for follow-up.  She has been doing well postoperatively.  Because of the diarrhea she was having back in December we had sent her for a colonoscopy, and it turned out she had a new colon cancer.  This was resected with no complications by Dr. Sullins.  She has been doing well.  Her energy level is good.  Her diarrhea is well-controlled.  She does have her stoma now which has been causing her no problems whatsoever.  She is active and feeling well.  She has recently palpated a nodule in her right chest wall area underneath her incision that she is not sure how long has been there.  It is not tender, and it has not been growing enlarging.

